{"key":"post-10261189","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10261189</id>\n<content>Jesus, trichoderma will NOT grow on plain gypsum.&amp;nbsp; It will however grow on peat moss and we use that in casing layers.&amp;nbsp; The idea of a non-nutritive casing layer is to make it somewhat inhospitable to molds.&amp;nbsp; If your casing layer was completely inert, such as perlite, it would never colonize.&amp;nbsp; Use gypsum in casing layers and substrates.&amp;nbsp; This has been established in mycology and by professional mushroom farms for decades.&amp;nbsp; It's not something new.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10261460</next>\n<prev>10261158</prev>\n<first>10257513</first>\n<last>14923768</last>\n<when>1241101698</when>\n<utime>04/30/09 05:28 PM</utime>\n</post>"}